          "input": {
            "content": "## Description\n\nThis PR addresses spec/autonomy decoupling and the permission regression found in ExitSpecMode approval flows.\n\n### Bugs identified, root cause, and fix\n\n1. **Spec mode and autonomy level were coupled in session/protocol paths**\n   - **Root cause:** The legacy combined `autonomyMode` enum was the source of truth for two orthogonal axes (spec-vs-auto interaction mode, and risk autonomy threshold), causing drift and overwrites when either axis changed independently.\n   - **User-visible symptom:** Toggling autonomy level (e.g. low → high) could silently flip interaction mode, or entering spec mode could reset autonomy level to Off.\n   - **Fix:** Migrated to decoupled-first handling (`interactionMode` + `autonomyLevel`) across CLI, daemon, frontend, and session flows, with legacy `autonomyMode` kept only for backward compatibility.\n\n2. **ExitSpecMode auto-run selection did not persist the chosen autonomy level**\n   - **Root cause:** Permission outcomes were processed twice in the JSON-RPC flow -- once in `JsonRpcProtocolAdapter`, then again in `PermissionRequestHandler`. The second pass could reset mode back to `normal`, discarding the user's low/medium/high selection.\n   - **User-visible symptom:** User selects \"auto-run (high)\" on an ExitSpecMode approval, but the session reverts to normal mode immediately after approval.\n   - **Fix:** Centralized outcome processing in `PermissionRequestHandler` (single owner). `JsonRpcProtocolAdapter` now forwards the raw permission outcome + approved tool IDs without applying autonomy side effects.\n\n3. **Cloud session template defaults used legacy autonomyMode path**\n   - **Root cause:** `useSessionDefaultSettings` resolved cloud template defaults through the legacy `autonomyMode` field, which couldn't express the decoupled axes independently.\n   - **User-visible symptom:** Cloud templates with a specific autonomy level preset would silently lose the level when the session initialized, falling back to defaults.\n   - **Fix:** Simplified `useSessionDefaultSettings` to resolve defaults through decoupled fields directly.\n\n4. **ModelSwitcher used legacy `currentAutonomyMode` for spec model display**\n   - **Root cause:** `ModelSwitcher` determined whether to show the spec-mode model by checking `currentAutonomyMode === AutonomyMode.Spec`. After decoupling, the canonical source of truth is `interactionMode`, but ModelSwitcher had no prop for it.\n   - **User-visible symptom:** If a caller set `interactionMode: Spec` without also setting the legacy `autonomyMode`, the trigger button would display the main model name instead of the spec model name.\n   - **Fix:** Added `currentInteractionMode` prop to `ModelSwitcher`. Checks `currentInteractionMode` first, falls back to `currentAutonomyMode` for backward compat.\n\n5. **Resolve+store+derive pattern duplicated 3 times, risking drift**\n   - **Root cause:** The logic to resolve decoupled fields, write them to the store, and derive `autonomyMode` was copy-pasted in `SessionStateManager.handleNotification`, `SessionStateManager.updateSessionSettings`, and `DaemonSessionController.loadSession` (~20 lines each).\n   - **User-visible symptom:** No immediate bug, but high change-amplification risk -- any future fix to resolution logic would need 3 identical edits, and a miss would cause silent inconsistency between load/notification/update paths.\n   - **Fix:** Extracted `applyInteractionSettings()` on `SessionStateManager`. All three call sites now delegate to it (-40 net lines).\n\n### Other changes\n\n- Marked `AutonomyModeSwitcher` as `@deprecated` (V1.0 input path only; replaced by `ChatComposerAutonomySelector` in V1.1).\n- Updated schemas/types/event payloads for the decoupled flow.\n\n## Related Issue\n\ncloses FAC-16122\n\n## Potential Risk & Impact\n\n- Compatibility risk in mixed-version clients still relying on legacy `autonomyMode` semantics.\n- Permission flow behavior changed in JSON-RPC mode; regressions here could affect tool approval resolution.\n- No known significant performance impact; changes are primarily control-flow and state/schema mapping.\n\n## How Has This Been Tested?\n\n**CLI tests:**\n```\nnpm --prefix apps/cli test -- src/agent/PermissionRequestHandler.test.ts src/adapters/JsonRpcProtocolAdapter.test.ts src/exec/streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.test.ts src/agent/tool-confirmation.test.ts\n```\n\n**Frontend tests (15 new tests across 5 files):**\n```\nnpm --prefix packages/frontend test -- --run src/services/session/utils/resolveInteractionSettings.test.ts src/features/sessions/hooks/useActiveSessionSettings.test.ts src/services/session/state/SessionStateManager.test.ts src/services/session/DaemonSessionController.test.ts src/features/sessions/hooks/useSessionDefaultSettings.test.tsx\n```\n\n**Component library tests:**\n```\nnpm --prefix packages/component-library test -- --run src/chat/ModelSwitcher/ModelSwitcher.test.tsx src/chat/DroidSessionChat.test.tsx\n```\n\n**Typecheck:** `npm run typecheck --filter=@factory/frontend --filter=@factory/component-library --filter=apps/cli`\n",
